.TH "TEMPORAL.DURATION.ADD" "3JS" "December 8, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Temporal.Duration.add \- Temporal.Duration.prototype.add()
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]add()\f[B]\f[R] method of \f[CR]Temporal.Duration\f[R]
instances returns a new \f[CR]Temporal.Duration\f[R] object with the sum
of this duration and a given duration.
The result is balanced.
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
add(other)
.EE
.SS Parameters
.TP
\f[B]other\f[R]
A string, an object, or a \f[CR]Temporal.Duration\f[R] instance
representing a duration to add to this duration.
It is converted to a \f[CR]Temporal.Duration\f[R] object using the same
algorithm as \f[CR]Temporal.Duration.from()\f[R].
.SS Return value
A new \f[CR]Temporal.Duration\f[R] object representing the sum of this
duration and \f[CR]other\f[R].
.SS Exceptions
.TP
\f[B]RangeError\f[R]
Thrown in one of the following cases:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Either \f[CR]this\f[R] or \f[CR]other\f[R] is a calendar duration (it
has a non\-zero \f[CR]years\f[R], \f[CR]months\f[R], or
\f[CR]weeks\f[R]), because calendar durations are ambiguous without a
calendar and time reference.
.IP \(bu 2
The sum of \f[CR]this\f[R] and \f[CR]other\f[R] overflows the maximum or
underflows the minimum representable duration, which is ±2\(ha53
seconds.
.RE
.SH DESCRIPTION
Non\-calendar durations unambiguously represent a fixed amount of time.
Internally, \f[CR]this\f[R] and \f[CR]other\f[R] are both converted to
nanoseconds (assuming 24\-hour days) and added together.
The result is then converted back to a \f[CR]Temporal.Duration\f[R]
object, so the result is always balanced or top\-heavy with the largest
possible unit being \f[CR]days\f[R].
.PP
If you want to perform addition or subtraction with a calendar duration,
you can add both durations to a starting point and then figure out the
difference between the two resulting instants; that is,
\f[CR]dur1 + dur2\f[R] is equivalent to
\f[CR](start + dur1 + dur2) \- start\f[R].
.PP
To add a duration to a date or time, use the \f[CR]add()\f[R] method of
the date or time object instead.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Using add()
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] d1 = Temporal.Duration.from({ hours: 1, minutes: 30 });
\f[B]const\f[R] d2 = Temporal.Duration.from({ hours: \-1, minutes: \-20 });

\f[B]const\f[R] d3 = d1.add(d2);
console.log(d3.toString()); \f[I]// \(dqPT10M\(dq\f[R]
.EE
.SS Adding calendar durations
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] d1 = Temporal.Duration.from({ days: 1 });
\f[B]const\f[R] d2 = Temporal.Duration.from({ months: 1 });

d1.add(d2); \f[I]// RangeError: for calendar duration arithmetic, use date arithmetic relative to a starting point\f[R]

\f[B]const\f[R] start = Temporal.PlainDateTime.from(\(dq2022\-01\-01T00:00\(dq); \f[I]// ISO 8601 calendar\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] result = start.add(d1).add(d2).since(start);
console.log(result.toString()); \f[I]// \(dqP32D\(dq\f[R]
.EE
.SH SEE ALSO
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]Temporal.Duration\f[R]
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]Temporal.Duration.prototype.subtract()\f[R]
